10) How does JVM perform garbage collection?
-->The JVM performs garbage collection (GC) using an automatic process based on the generational 
    hypothesis (most objects die young) and the core mark-and-sweep algorithm to identify and reclaim memory from unused objects.

11) Is JVM platform dependent or independent?
-->platform-dependent:
    The JVM (Java Virtual Machine) is platform-dependent, while Java code is platform-independent. 


12) How does JVM handle bytecode?
-->The Java Virtual Machine (JVM) handles bytecode through a multi-stage process involving loading,
    verification, and execution using a combination of an interpreter and a Just-In-Time (JIT) compiler. 


13) What are native methods in JVM?
-->A native method in Java is a method declared within Java code but whose implementation is written in another programming language, such as C or C++.

14) How does the JVM differ for different operating systems?
-->The JVM is platform-dependent; a specific version of the JVM is required for each operating system and hardware architecture,
    which then executes the same, platform-independent Java bytecode. The differences are in how each specific JVM implementation 
    interacts with the native features of the underlying OS. 

    Key differences and platform-specific aspects include:
    Native Code Implementation: The JVM itself is a software program written in native code (like C/C++) that must be compiled for a 
    specific platform (e.g., Windows on x86, Linux on AArch64, macOS on x64/ARM).


15) In which order does the JVM load classes (hierarchy of class loaders)?
-->The JVM loads classes using a parent-first delegation model, where a request to load a class is passed up the hierarchy
    of classloaders, starting from the application classloader and going up to the bootstrap classloader.
    The hierarchy of built-in classloaders is as follows:
    Bootstrap ClassLoader (also known as Primordial ClassLoader): This is the root classloader and is implemented in native code (not Java).
    It has no parent and is responsible for loading core Java runtime classes (like java.lang.Object) from the standard JDK directory
    (e.g., JAVA_HOME/lib/rt.jar in older versions or the Java Runtime Image in Java 9+ module systems).

    Platform ClassLoader (formerly Extension ClassLoader): This classloader is a child of the Bootstrap ClassLoader and loads
    platform-specific extension classes. It loads classes from the extension directories
    (e.g., JAVA_HOME/lib/ext or other directories specified by the java.ext.dirs property in older Java versions).

    Application ClassLoader (also known as System ClassLoader): This is the default classloader for user-defined classes and is a child of the 
    Platform ClassLoader. It is responsible for loading classes from the application's classpath, which is specified by the CLASSPATH environment 
    variable or the -classpath command-line option


16) What is the delegation model of class loading?
-->The delegation model of class loading in Java is a hierarchical mechanism where a ClassLoader delegates loading requests 
    to its parent before attempting to load a class itself. It ensures that core Java classes are prioritized and loaded only
    once, preventing conflicts and improving security. The process moves from the application loader to the extension loader, and finally
    the bootstrap loader. 

        Hierarchy: When a ClassLoader receives a request to load a class, it first delegates the task to its parent ClassLoader.

        Parent-First: The request travels up the hierarchy (Application -> Extension -> Bootstrap).
        Loading Responsibility: A loader only attempts to load the class if its parent and all ancestors fail to find it.
        Preventing Duplication: This model ensures that core classes (like java.lang.Object) are loaded by the bootstrap class loader,
                                    preventing application-level loaders from replacing them, which enhances security.

